```{r message=FALSE, warning=FALSE}
library(tidyverse)
library(tmap)
library(sf)
library(climateR)
```

```{r}
borders_hires <- rnaturalearth::ne_countries(country = "Switzerland", 
                                             scale = "large", 
                                             returnclass = "sf")
```

<br/>

The variables available from the TerraClim normals are the following:
```{r}
catalog %>% 
  filter(id == "terraclim") %>% 
  select(varname, units, description)
```


<br/> 

Now we will use the `getTerraClim()` from `climateR` to get the TerraClim monthly precipitation data.  The `AOI` specifies  the spatial object that describes the area of interest.  The `varname` argument specifies the variable download.  The `startDate` argument specifies the start date for the time period of interest and the `endDate` specifies the end date for our period of interest


::: {.callout-important}
The server that provides TerraClim data was out of service on 18-Feb-2026 (though seemed to be working again on 22-Feb-2026).  It is not clear if this is a short-term issue and will be resolved shortly or if this may be a longer-term issue.  We can try this code in class on 24-Feb-2026, however if it doesn't work then we will skip it and get monthly precipitation data from the CHIRPS dataset.  

:::

```{r eval = F}
climate_raster <- getTerraClim(
  AOI = borders_hires,
  varname = "ppt",
  startDate = "2021-01-01",
  endDate = "2021-12-01",
  verbose = T,
  dryrun = FALSE
)
```

```{r}
climate_raster <- climate_raster$ppt
```

Now let's crop and mask the raster.
```{r}
climate_raster <- terra::crop(climate_raster, borders_hires)

climate_raster <- terra::mask(climate_raster, borders_hires)
```
```{r}
switzerland_tot_prcp <- sum(climate_raster)
```


```{r}
terra::plot(switzerland_tot_prcp)
```

```{r}
switzerland_mean_prcp <- mean(climate_raster)
```



